The Ukraine on the way to Europe
"The East is East and the West is West, and they will never find each other," Rudyard Kipling once said.
The Ukraine is undoubtedly in the East, but in Eastern Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the predominant goal for many of us.
The way there was, however, not always paved with successes, if it was paved at all.
The result of the parliamentary elections on March 31 has shown that the Ukrainians are still determined to continue on this path.
I am a social democrat and was never a member of the communist party, although I was quite successful as a lawyer at the time of the Soviet Union.
For me, it is beyond question that our "Soviet" heritage is largely responsible for Ukraine's difficulties in finding its way to Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural cultivation areas were virtually paralyzed due to outdated machinery parks and the lethargy of state-led agriculture following the Soviet model.
The rural population sank deep into dirt and poverty.
Low wages make life here very burdensome, the pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is enormous.
But our Soviet heritage does not justify everything.
We have completely botched the reform on our own.
For often we wanted to import proven concepts from the West - private ownership, free market economy, strict observance of human rights, the creation of civil society, representative democracy - in a weakened form and thought that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic inclinations in politics, the Supreme Council (the parliament of Ukraine) has adopted citizens' rights and criminal law, land, family, and economic rights over the years, which is equivalent to a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that has been disconnected from European history for centuries was often painful, but it has gained momentum, even though we don't necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as open, sentimental, friendly, and family-conscious, but also chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Still, we are Europeans.
This can be seen on the streets and squares of Kiev.
Today, drivers allow pedestrians to cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still need to take precautions against reckless drivers).
In Kiev, there is now a lively café scene and friendly public spaces where people can pause and enjoy life.
Young people learn English, German, and French, and they can handle computers and surf the internet in internet cafes.
But this is just a romantic digression from someone who loves Kiev very much.
The sober view of a professional politician, which I am, sees deeper changes.
In the last ten years, a development from total rejection of reforms to a policy of half-hearted reforms from corrupt motives to a gradual introduction of Western practices has taken place.
The administrative reform reflects this very clearly.
Initially, the reform of the state evoked a hostile mood both among bureaucrats and among ordinary citizens.
A drastic and unconsidered reduction of civil servants in the public service began.
It was a reform "by the book": the state had to shrink, one thought, and then the government would run smoothly.
No one thought about how countries like France or Switzerland could somehow thrive with large state apparatuses.
For the problem is not just a problem of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government is not necessarily better just because you apply a red pen led us to the second stage in our reform process.
The state was slowly reformed in a more thoughtful way.
New departments and positions for state secretaries with a clearly defined area of responsibility were set up.
By doing so, the work of the government ministries was stabilized.
At the beginning, the authority transferred to these new areas was a bit too extensive to facilitate their work more effectively.
Now they function more or less normally.
Ukrainians may get annoyed sometimes with these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they are increasingly accepting them as necessary (if only reluctantly).
Reasonable politicians also accept them.
Only radicals and populists - of whom there are still too many among us - can afford to take a indifferent stance towards a more efficient state.
Taming our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
The Ukraine was too long a province of the USSR and the tsarist empire, the most important, but still a province.
This has shaped our mentality. Because radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming feeling of inadequacy and our efforts to deny this have led to the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial can by no means admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
In the measure in which we shed our provincial impulse to defend ourselves, we open ourselves to the best of what others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mocked as "the sick man of Europe".
Since 1991, Ukrainians have had to recognize that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
In the course of a decade, we may have contributed ourselves to becoming even sicker, but the recently held elections, which brought the Communists to their predominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly reduced the power of "the powerful parties" around President Kuchma, have pushed our provincial radicals to the fringes of politics.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As European outsiders or at least as a people on the periphery of Europe, we want to establish a society in which there are no outsiders or peripheral residents.
As the great and at the time already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all the achievements of nature, the most astonishing is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long, arduous path to Europe has helped a weak new nation to become strong and survive.
